  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range. Let your body wake up gradually — no rushing the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic effort. Conversational pace throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace in the final 5 minutes. A few minutes of light stretching after is a good investment.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond the easy first 5 minutes of the run itself.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing, then do light calf and hip flexor stretches — especially worth doing given your Achilles history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the aerobic tone for the week. At VDOT 46.7, your easy range is 5:22–5:56/km — aim for the middle of that band today (around 5:39/km), which matches your recent easy run rhythm. This run builds aerobic base without creating fatigue that would compromise Tuesday's quality session. Think of it as active recovery from the weekend long run.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to get blood flowing, then 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval pace with full recovery. This primes your neuromuscular system before the hard work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 × 1 km at 4:11/km (251 sec/km). This is your interval pace — it should feel hard but controlled, not an all-out sprint. You're targeting VO2Max stimulus, which means sustained effort at roughly 95–98% max HR by the end of each rep. If you're gasping after rep 1, ease back slightly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval — approximately 2 minutes. Keep moving; don't stop completely. The goal is partial recovery so the next rep is still challenging.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"1.6 km easy jog to flush lactate and begin the recovery process. This is not optional — it meaningfully speeds recovery for tomorrow.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by 4–6 × 20-second strides at interval pace with full walk recovery between each. This mirrors what you've been doing successfully in recent weeks.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"1.6 km easy jog, then 5 minutes of dynamic stretching. Pay particular attention to calf stretches given your Achilles history — gentle, sustained holds rather than aggressive bouncing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This session mirrors your successful 5 × 1 km workout from March 15th. At the maintenance goal, the aim isn't to push harder — it's to sustain the VO2Max stimulus you've already built. Interval training at 4:11/km stresses your aerobic ceiling, which keeps your fitness from drifting downward even without a race on the horizon. The key is consistency of effort across all 5 reps, not heroics on rep 1. If the last rep feels similar to the first, you've nailed it.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — at or near the slow end of your easy range (5:50–5:56/km). The day after intervals, your legs will likely feel heavy. That's normal and expected. Honour the pace ceiling today.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Just start slowly and stay slow.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2–3 minutes walking, then calf and Achilles stretches. Consider a foam roll of the calves if they feel tight after yesterday's intervals.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a deliberate recovery run — short, slow, and purposeful. After Tuesday's VO2Max work, your body is in repair mode. Running easy today promotes blood flow and active recovery without adding meaningful stress. This is one of those sessions where going slower is genuinely better. Your recent training history shows you've been running these at 5:56/km, which is exactly right. Resist any urge to push — Thursday's tempo depends on you arriving fresh.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":54,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Take the full warmup — threshold work demands a properly primed cardiovascular system. Don't shortchange this.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km, 268 sec/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you could speak a word or two but not hold a conversation. If you're gasping, you've gone too fast. If you're chatting freely, you've gone too easy. The sweet spot is sustained, focused effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to bring heart rate down gradually. Don't stop abruptly after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog at 5:50–5:56/km. You might add 2–3 light strides in the final minute of the warmup to prime your legs for threshold pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then 5 minutes of stretching. Focus on hip flexors, calves, and hamstrings. Rehydrate and have a small carbohydrate-protein snack within 30 minutes if this run falls more than 3 hours after your last meal.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This session replicates your March 17th tempo run almost exactly — 2 km warmup, 8 km at 4:28/km, 2 km cooldown. That's intentional. In a maintenance phase, threshold work is your most important quality session because it directly sustains your lactate threshold, which is the strongest predictor of marathon performance. The 8 km continuous tempo is a meaningful stimulus without being excessive. Your recent execution of this session was excellent — the goal this week is simply to replicate that quality.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy, conversational effort throughout. Aim for the middle of your easy range — around 5:39/km. This is a bridge run between Thursday's quality work and Sunday's long run. Keep it honest.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start the first 5 minutes at the slow end of easy pace before settling into your comfortable rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Light stretching post-run. Prioritise sleep and hydration tonight — Sunday's long run is two days away.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run keeps your aerobic engine ticking without adding fatigue. At 8 km, it's enough to maintain aerobic stimulus but short enough to leave you fresh for Sunday. This mirrors your March 19th run (8 km, 5:39/km), which is a solid template. Think of today as maintenance mileage — it's not glamorous, but it's the connective tissue of a well-built training week.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Low-impact aerobic activity of your choice — cycling, swimming, elliptical, or yoga all work well. Keep effort genuinely easy (RPE 3–4). The goal is blood flow and mobility, not fitness gains. This is a rest day with movement.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed. Ease into whatever activity you choose.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5–10 minutes of gentle stretching, particularly calves, Achilles, and hips. Given your Achilles history, Saturday is a good day for a focused mobility routine.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your buffer day before the long run. Cross-training keeps you moving without the impact stress of running, which is especially relevant given your Achilles history. If your legs feel genuinely tired from the week, it's completely fine to make this a full rest day instead — listen to what your body is telling you. The long run on Sunday is the priority; Saturday exists to support it.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the slow end of easy pace (5:50–5:56/km) for the first 10 minutes. Long runs should always begin conservatively — you have plenty of time to find your rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":98,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic pace in the 5:22–5:56/km range. Your recent long runs have been at 5:56/km, which is perfectly appropriate. There's no need to push the pace on long runs in a maintenance phase — the aerobic stimulus comes from duration, not speed. Stay conversational throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 10 minutes. Finish feeling like you had a little more in the tank — that's the right long run feeling.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start slowly and build into your easy pace over the first 10–15 minutes. No strides or surges needed before a long run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of walking after you finish, then a thorough stretching routine — calves, Achilles, hip flexors, hamstrings, and glutes. Rehydrate well and have a recovery meal or snack within 45 minutes. This is when your body does its best adaptation work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the cornerstone of your week. At 20 km, it matches your recent long run volume exactly, which is appropriate for a maintenance phase — you're not building, you're sustaining. The aerobic adaptations from long runs (mitochondrial density, fat oxidation, cardiac efficiency) are maintained by consistent exposure, not by pushing pace or distance. Run at 5:22–5:56/km and focus on time on feet. Carry water or plan a route with fountains, and consider a small carbohydrate source (gel or chews) around the 60–75 minute mark if you haven't eaten recently before the run. Your 120-minute cap is respected here — at your current pace this comes in around 118 minutes.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
